{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17643667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17643667"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:55:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:55:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18003"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18003"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.45,0.35,0,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10717"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78844"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10717"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18003"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64193"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24947"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24950"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27041"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78844","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78844"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe atlas is the name give to the C1 cervical vertebra (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a characteristic feature of the atlas (C1 vertebra)?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Articulation with the thoracic vertebrae","Bifid spinous process","Large lateral masses","Presence of a body","Presence of a dens"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elarge lateral masses\u003C/strong\u003E are a characteristic feature of the atlas (C1 vertebra). These structures support the weight of the skull and articulate with the occipital condyles, allowing for the nodding motion of the head.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe atlas does not have a \u003Cstrong\u003Ebody\u003C/strong\u003E; instead, it is a ring-like structure. This is a unique feature that differentiates it from other cervical vertebrae.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edens\u003C/strong\u003E is a feature of the axis (C2 vertebra), not the atlas. The dens acts as a pivot that allows the atlas and skull to rotate on the axis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe atlas lacks a \u003Cstrong\u003Ebifid spinous process\u003C/strong\u003E, which is a feature of other cervical vertebrae. Instead, it has a posterior arch with a small tubercle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe atlas does not \u003Cstrong\u003Earticulate with the thoracic vertebrae\u003C/strong\u003E; it articulates with the occipital bone of the skull and the axis (C2 vertebra).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The atlas (C1 vertebra) is unique in its structure, lacking a body and spinous process.","The atlas has large lateral masses that support the skull and articulate with the occipital condyles.","The atlas allows for the nodding motion of the head, known as flexion and extension."],"references":["Middleditch, A., \u0026 Oliver, J. (2005). Functional anatomy of the spine. Elsevier Health Sciences","Cramer, G. D., \u0026 Darby, S. A. (2013). Clinical anatomy of the spine, spinal cord, and ANS","Bogduk, N. (2016). Functional anatomy of the spine. Handbook of clinical neurology, 136, 675-688","Adigun OO, Reddy V, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Back, Spinal Cord. 2023 Jun 26. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725689","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]}